The test can be performed in respiratory or blood samples.
The results are normally made available from a few hours a day.
Generally, this test is performed in nasopharyngeal rubble, although the throat rubble is also used. Several laboratories and companies are developing serological tests, capable of detecting antibodies.
On 6 April 2020, none of these had proved sufficiently accurate to be approved for general use.
